**How to create CICD Pipeline by using AWS EC2 jenkins and docker**.

For carrying out such projects, we need to know the steps and requirements for this. So the steps are as follows:

Step 1: First we create an EC2 instance on AWS using Ubuntu image; An Amazon EC2(Elastic Compute Cloud) instance is a server provided by Amazon to facilitate the user to run the application and host websites and other things like data storage and processing without needing a physical computer. It can be customized as per the need of the user in terms of memory, storage and networking capacity.

Step 2: After creating the EC2 instance we’ll install Jenkins and configure it on Ubuntu OS; So about Jenkins it is an open source automation server which facilitates CI/CD in software development, and what exactly CI/CD is? It stands for Continuous Integration and Continuous Deploying of code which is self explanatory that it will create a continuous flow in the service, whenever any changes are made in the code and pushed on github then there is an instant change in the deployment of the service. And how does Jenkins actually do that? By using different plugins and various tools and technology. Jenkins ensures that the changes are consistently tested and deployed.

Step 3: Then we’ll install node and npm, what node.js do? It runs the javascript code on server side instead of web browser which allows deployers to make a scalable and high-performance application. npm (Node Package Manager) is a package manager for Node.js, which allows developers to easily install, manage, and share reusable code libraries or "packages" that extend the functionality of their applications.

Step 4: Then we’ll install Docker on ubuntu and a little about docker is \-.Docker is an open-source platform that automates the deployment. It creates lightweight, portable containers. These containers have an application and its dependencies. Docker simplifies the development process by isolating the application making it easier to scale, test and deploy.

Step 5: We’re gonna use GitHub, GitHub is also an open-source platform where developers push their source code of their project and from there push it to deployment, but that’s not it, here many people can work upon a single project and give their contribution in that project and if anyone is working on a different portion of a single project then they can make a branch on that project and after completing that portion merge that branch on the main/master branch. It is called a version control system.

Step 6: Creation of CI/CD pipeline, CI/CD is made up of two things CI that is Continuous Integration which is developers can continuously and frequently merge their codes in the shared repository and automate the test run to detect any issue early, and CD that is Continuous Delivery or Deployment, the code is automated for deployment after passing the tests.

**Now we’ll start**

1. **Creation of EC2 instance on AWS**  
   

First of all I have logged in my AWS console where I will be creating my EC2 instance. Amazon provide that facility and charge for it but I have used the free tier of it   
![][image1] 

This is how the screen looks when Logged In. There is this EC2 written on the screen, from here run EC2 instance by clicking it. It asks for details for new instances. Remember to select Ubuntu to create an Ubuntu image, then I select instance type and that will be the free one. 

An Ubuntu image is a pre-built package of the Ubuntu operating system, designed for use in environments like Docker containers or virtual machines. It includes the essential components of Ubuntu, such as the Linux kernel, shell, and basic utilities, making it a lightweight and efficient base for deploying applications. It is customized and configured as per the software requirement of the developer.

Then select the key pair for logging in to the Ubuntu instance. Here two options of key to download will appear, .ppm(openSSH) and .ppk(PuTTY). I select the .ppk file and it will be downloaded in your system for connection.  

After all the settings are done click on Launch Instance.  
![][image2]

Here’s my instance that has been created and from here I will take a public IPv4 address and copy it.

Now for Ubuntu I have downloaded PuTTY from its official website.

What PuTTY is ? It is a terminal emulator that supports various network protocols such as SSH. PuTTY provides a command-line interface that allows users to execute commands, manage files, and perform administrative tasks on the remote machine.

![][image3]![][image4]  
Here in Host Name I have given the public IPv4 address which I copied from the EC2 instance. And placed the .ppk file in Auth credentials.

After that run the PuTTY for further.

2. **Installation of Jenkins** 

For Downloading Jenkins search google “install jenkins for ubuntu” or visit   
[https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable/](https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable/) this url and fetch the commands for installation of jenkins in ubuntu 

Before downloading Jenkins it is mandatory to add a key to the system and this will be done by the command.  
![][image5]  
After this just the download command is run on the PuTTY CLI. It will take a little time as it will download all the required stuff on your system. 

Issue, the PuTTY on my system was closing automatically, so I run it after every few minutes. If I leave the PuTTY CLI ideal it leaves the connection and stops responding.

3. **Installation of Node and npm**

Go to google and search “Install node.js on ubuntu” or what you can do is run below commands 

* sudo apt-get update    
* sudo apt-get install node.js


to confirm if node is installed 

* node \-v

And now download npm (node package manager) by following commands

* sudo apt-get update   
* sudo apt-get install npm

 To confirm jenkins server is running, run a command: 

* systemctl status jenkins

![][image6]

By default jenkins server runs on port 8080\. So it run on server \<your public IPv4 address\>:8080/

A port is a communication endpoint that allows different applications or services to interact with each other over a network. When developing applications, especially those involving client-server models, specifying the correct port ensures that data is directed to the right application.

Issue, security group might be blocking the connection. So edit the inbound rule and allow port 8080 to run.

Copy and paste the path from here in PuTTY CLI with a command 

* sudo cat \<path\>  
  And get the admin password from there.   
  Put that password here and it will start your basic configuration for your Jenkins .  
    
  


Start Jenkins instance or Jenkins CI/CD pipeline. Add the gitHub URL to your Jenkins server. Create an item on your server and enter the details of your project. 

4. **Installation of Docker.**

To install docker, run a few simple commands. 

* sudo apt-get update  
* sudo apt-get install docker.io  
  


Now generate the SSH key, why? To allow Jenkins to enter the EC2 server, it requires an authorization key to enter the EC2 server. The keys are SSH public and SSH private keys.

An SSH (Secure Shell) key is a cryptographic key used to securely authenticate and connect to remote servers. It’s a fundamental tool in the development, deployment, and management of applications, especially in environments where secure access to servers is necessary.   

Command for generation of keys:

* ssh-keygen  
* sshkey 

![][image7]

Private key is in sskkey and public key is in sshkey.pub 

* cat sshkey.pub

Go to gitHub account \> settings \> SSH and GPG keys \> Add new.  
Paste the copied SSH public key. With this our GitHub has access to the public server.

Again go to jenkins server and configuration \> credentials and there paste the private key in credential. With this Jenkins is able to connect to the system. 

Now build the pipeline. An automated process in which the building, testing and deploying of the application is involved. It has a sequence of stages that the code has to pass through from development to production.  By automating these steps, a pipeline reduces the chances of human error, speeds up the development cycle, and ensures consistent quality across all deployments. 

![][image8]

With this the Basic CI/CD pipeline is created

5. **Running the code.**  
   

Run the command on the PuTTY CLI,

* sudo npm install  
* npm start

Issue, this will not work, why? Because of the security group. To run the code or start the application it is mandatory to allow your server to access the port, by editing inbound rules.

![][image9]

Now a docker file is created and how it’s gonna be done? Yes, by a command,

* vim Dockerfile

The command ‘`vim Dockerfile’` opens a file named ‘`Dockerfile’` in the Vim text editor. The ‘`Dockerfile’` itself is a script that contains instructions for Docker to build a custom Docker image, typically specifying the base image, environment variables, dependencies, and commands to run. Using Vim, you can edit the ‘`Dockerfile’` to customize how your Docker image

![][image10]  
CORRECTION: in above image its not dockerfile it is Dockerfile, naming convention is essential.

Now build the docker file and how will it be done? Ofcourse, by a command

* docker run \-d –name vipul \-p 4000:4000 node-app


This command runs a Node.js application in a Docker container named "vipul", detaches it to run in the background, and maps port 4000 of the host machine to port 4000 of the container, making the application accessible on the host machine via port 4000\. 

![][image11]

Now create the trigger to make it continuous, for this go to the repository \> settings \> webhooks and create a webhook there for the trigger, this trigger will make the CI/CD pipeline continuous.

Issue, install a plugin on jenkins server for creating webhooks otherwise it might not work.

Once the webhook is created, configure the build command in the configure section in Jenkins server. 

* docker build . \-t node-app123  
* docker run \-d –name node-app1 \-p 4000:4000 node-app1

And with that, automation in the pipeline is complete and now the app will deploy on its own once any changes were made in the gitHub repository.
